INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2270880f-1805-4339-9121-70893ad5fb5e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Vite TypeScript — Transpile-Only Mode and When to Add Type Checking Back$escape$,
  $escape$Vite never runs `tsc` during dev or build by default. It uses esbuild to strip TypeScript types — pure transpilation, zero type checking. This is why `vite dev` starts in milliseconds regardless of project size. Your type errors are invisible to Vite itself.

To add type safety without sacrificing Vite's speed, run `tsc --noEmit` as a separate process. Wire it into your CI pipeline or as a parallel npm script using `concurrently`. Never block `vite build` on type checking in local dev — let esbuild do what it does fastest.

For the build step specifically, `vite build` will happily emit broken JS if your types are wrong. The idiomatic fix is a `build` script that runs `tsc --noEmit && vite build` — TypeScript gates the emit, Vite handles the bundling. You can also use `vite-plugin-checker` to surface type errors as HMR overlays during dev without blocking the server startup. Configure it with `typescript: true` and it spawns a background `tsc` worker.$escape$,
  $escape$// package.json scripts
{
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "vite",
    "type-check": "tsc --noEmit",
    "build": "tsc --noEmit && vite build",
    "dev:checked": "concurrently \"vite\" \"tsc --noEmit --watch\""
  }
}

// vite.config.ts — optional in-dev overlay via vite-plugin-checker
import checker from 'vite-plugin-checker'
export default {
  plugins: [
    checker({ typescript: true })
  ]
}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
